{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ea217d5a-8bc8-4760-8ecc-a96c12d04dd8","content":"With Microsoft.Testing.Platform the VSTest adapter flags are replaced by built-in extensions. The equivalent command is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --collect-coverage \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump \\\n  --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nYou'll also need these NuGet packages in your test project:\n\n| Old flag | New flag | Required package |\n|---|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--collect-coverage` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `--hangdump` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\nFor **Cobertura format**, add this to your test `.csproj` (or a `Directory.Build.props`):\n\n```xml\n<TestingExtensionCodeCoverageFormat>cobertura</TestingExtensionCodeCoverageFormat>\n```\n\n> **Note:** `--filter` syntax stays the same when invoked via `dotnet test`. If you later invoke the test executable directly, use `--treenode-filter` with the new filter syntax instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9a3eb671-e885-4566-95c3-286e54c60cc3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. Let me provide the equivalent command.\n\nKey differences with Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n- `--filter` becomes `--filter`(same) or `--treenode-filter`\n- `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` becomes `--collect-coverage` (with Microsoft.CodeCoverage) or you use a different approach\n- `--blame-crash` becomes `--crashdump`\n\n\n- `--blame-hang` and `--blame-hang-timeout` become `--hangdump` and `--hangdump-timeout`\n\nNow I'm mapping out the exact package requirements and command syntax for the new testing platform, since some features like TRX reporting and code coverage need specific NuGet packages to work properly.\n\nWhen using `dotnet test` as the entry point, there's some backward compatibility with VSTest options, but switching fully to Microsoft.Testing.Platform means either continuing with `dotnet test` and letting it translate the flags, or running the test app directly with the new syntax.","outputTokens":966,"requestId":"7038:83273:E1D5E97:F803942:69F2A88A"},"id":"51f193aa-8a90-4e5a-ae6b-ae023d749d2e","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:55:56.316Z","parentId":"161ae39e-62c9-40e2-b29f-5b8bf89f0865"}
